GIS-Clinical Collaboration: Web-based Report

Martin Gleason, MS

11/10/2019

The Ask

DCPO Halawa and Data Analyst Loftus asked if it would be possible to use the Cook County Medical Examiner Office(ME) data to supplement the department’s internal tracking of department involved youth killed in gun-releated deaths. Due to confidentiality concerns regarding department data, this report demonstrates how the the ME’s data can be transformed to support this research. It does not allow for the identification of specific youth. This report is a prototype that can help illustrate the possibilities of GIS powered reports and dashboards within the department’s constraints regarding confidentiality.

Importing the Data

Importing the medical examiner’s (ME) office data is simple task: The Cook County Open Data website has a link that, when incorporated into the R code of the report, allows for direct connection to the Open Data Portal. This eliminates the need of downloading files, ensures the most up to date data, and simplifies the data cleaning process.

Cleaning Data

Even though this data is coming from directly from the Medical Examiner’s database, the data does need to be cleaned to focus on the department’s key performance indicators. Exploring the data in a tabular format assists in determining which features need to be removed, added, or modified.

For the department’s purposes, a number of features should be removed to keep the data clean including: the age-range of interest to the department (15-26) and limiting cause of death to gun related incidents. A feature that needs to be modified is the race of the young person The way the ME classifies race is complicated. Race is listed as Black, White, Other, Asian, NA, Unknown, Am. Indian, with Latino being listed as a separate factor. For the department’s needs, the ME’s data needs to add Latino to race. This is a simple cleaning function in R, that creates the follow categories: Black, White, Other, Asian, NA, Unknown, White Latino, Latino, Am. Indian, Black Latino, NA Latino, Unknown Latino, Am. Indian Latino, Asian Latino

Visualizing the Data

The cleaned ME data set has following 27 columns: casenumber, incident_date, death_date, age, gender, race, latino, manner, primarycause, gunrelated, opioids, incident_street, longitude, latitude, objectid, location.type, location.coordinates, cold_related, heat_related, residence_zip, incident_zip, secondarycause, primarycause_lineb, primarycause_linec, residence_city, incident_city, source. Displaying all of this data in a single column is not useful on paper, but because this report is web based, we can add scroll bars to the table in order to view all the entries.

In short, the data can be filtered, selected and summarized for descriptive statistics, or displayed as a variety of graphs. Additionally, this data can be combined with internal data sets maintained by the department to determine what, if any, connections exist between youth who were killed in gun-related incidents and department programs and interventions. Adding this layer of data, while beyond the scope of this report, is well within the capability of the Office of the Chief Judge and the Department. With the impending release of the new case management system, cFive Supervisor, extending reporting features should be explored in additional projects.

GIS

Extending department capability with Geographic Information Systems (GIS) is another feature that can be added to the department’s analytic capability. The ME’s office already uses Cook County’s GIS(CCGIS) department to map the deaths and shooting incidents; however, the department has other geographic areas of interest. These include: police district, judicial district, Cook County Commissioner District and a yet-to-be-defined probation district. The Cook County Medical Examiner Office(ME) GIS dashboards present an impressive starting point for the department’s own GIS enabled reports.

It is well within the capacity of the department and CCGIS to build more interactive web reports. The barriers to this are policy driven, not technical. CCGIS needs sample data of at least 500 records to design our dashboards and reports, and the Office of the Chief Judge (OCJ) prefers to keep all data on it’s own servers. While negotations between OCJ and CCGIS are onging, to demonstrate the basic capability of this type of analysis, this prototype report will show gun-releated incidents per Cook County Commissioner Districts

Cook County Shooting Incidents by Commissioner District: 2016 - Today

Displaying Reports

Using the data and methods contained in this document, creating a GIS-informed report that runs regularly would be a relatively simple task. Creating a dashboard or app to display the same data would only be marginally more intensive. It would require installing R and RStudio on the Chief Judge’s servers. Given that OCJ has already begun the process of deploying Linux servers to support the new case plan system, adding another Linux instance on the OCJ intranet is neither a technical nor a cost prohibitive step. The most pressing concern about a dashboard/app would be getting permission from County stakeholders to share data between departments and approve the use of an internal web server.

The advantages of a dashboard/app would be the ability to filter the data sets and display them in real time, instead of “hard coding” results like this report. This method would increase collaboration, free up staff time for other analysis, generate less paper, and allow for easy access for all OCJ staff. These tools would also supplement the dashboard and report ability of the department’s new case management system, cFive. cFive’s demonstrated dashboards, while customizable, do not have the same capabilities (GIS, importing ME data, etc) as this report. The methods demonstrated in this prototype can be directly applied to cFive’s reporting structure.

Recap and Next Steps

Medical Examiner office and court data can be easily combined to track and measure shooting deaths of court involved youth. Collecting, cleaning, and visualizing this data was demonstrated in this prototype and can be deployed to the department shortly after cFive’s reporting system goes live. Expanding this capacity into dashboards is possible with a minor addition to the OCJ’s infrastructure. The barrier to dashboard development is ensuring that the dashboards are not accessible to the public. While this is a technical issue that is beyond the scope of this report, the Office of the Chief Judge has already begun to deploy an additional server to host cFive’s reporting services. An additional Linux server, configured to host dashboards and R functionality, would be a mid scale IT project that could dramatically increase the department’s analytic capability without cost to the department’s capital expenditures. Such a project is the logical next step of this analysis, and can begin once cFive’s reporting feature goes live.
